                                    <cell><m>30500</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                        </table>
                    </li>
                        <li><p>When we use graphing technology we see the entire function but in this context the plane is only on a parabolic path from <m>[0,25]</m> seconds, which is the domain, and the range of <m>[30500,33000]</m> feet.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Let's look at the remote-controlled airplane dive from <xref ref="example-remote-control-airplane-quadratic-application">Example</xref>. This time we will use technology to answer the questions.</p>

<!-- TODO: This one could be interactive. I didn't fix graph issues -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The owner of a remote-controlled airplane is going to do a stunt dive where the plane dives toward the ground and back up along a parabolic path. The height of the plane is given by the function <m>H(t)=0.7t^2-23t+200</m>, for <m>0 \le t \le 30</m>. The height is measured in feet and the time, <m>t</m>, is measured in seconds.
                    <ol label="a.">
                        <li><p>Determine the starting height of the plane as the dive begins.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Determine the height of the plane after <m>5</m> seconds.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Will the plane hit the ground, and if so, at what time?</p></li>
                        <li><p>If the plane does not hit the ground, what is the closest it gets to the ground, and at what time?</p></li>
                        <li><p>At what time(s) will the plane have a height of <m>50</m> feet?</p></li>
                        <li><p>State the domain and the range of the function in interval form and in context.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We have graphed the function and we will find the key information and put it in context.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>H(t)=0.7t^2-23t+200</m></caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-20,ymax=220,xmin=-5,xmax=35,
                                        xtick={empty},ytick={empty},
                                        minor ytick={20,40,...,220},
                                        minor xtick={0,5,..., 35},
                                        xlabel={\scriptsize time in seconds},ylabel={\scriptsize height in feet}]
                                \addplot+[domain=-0.848:33.705] {0.7*x^2-23*x+200} node[pos=0.70,right] {\scriptsize $H(t)$};
                                \addplot+[domain=-5:35] {50} node[pos=0.70,right] node[above left] {\scriptsize $y=50$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(0,200)} node[below right] {\scriptsize $(0,200)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(5,102.5)} node[right] {\scriptsize $(5,102.5)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(16.43,11.07)} node[left] {\scriptsize $(16.43,11.07)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(30,140)} node[left] {\scriptsize $(30,140)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(8.971, 50)} node[below left] {\scriptsize $(8.97, 50)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot] coordinates {(23.886, 50)} node[below right] {\scriptsize $(23.89, 50)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>
                    <ol label="a.">
                        <li><p>The starting height is the vertical intercept, which is <m>(0,200)</m>. When the stunt begins, the plane has a height of <m>200</m> feet.</p></li>

                        <li><p>When <m>x=5</m>, the <m>y</m>-value is <m>102.5</m>, or <m>H(5)=102.5</m>. This means that after <m>5</m> seconds, the plane is <m>102.5</m> feet above the ground.</p></li>

                        <li><p>From the graph we can see that the parabola does not touch or cross the <m>x</m>-axis, which represents the ground. This means the plane does not hit the ground and there are no real solutions to the equation <m>H(t)=0</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>The lowest point is the vertex, which is approximately <m>(16.43, 11.07)</m>. The minimum height of the plane is about <m>11</m> feet, which occurs after about <m>16.4</m> seconds.</p></li>

                        <li><p>We will graph the horizontal line <m>y=50</m> and look for the points of intersection. The plane will be <m>50</m> feet above the ground about 9 seconds and 24 seconds after the plane begins the stunt.</p></li>

                        <li><p>The domain for this problem is given in the problem statement becasue only part of the parabola represents the path of the plane. The domain is <m>[0,30]</m>. For the range we look at the possible heights of the plane and see that it is <m>[11,200]</m>. The plane is doing this stunt from <m>0</m> to <m>30</m> seconds and its height ranges from about <m>11</m> to <m>200</m> feet above the ground.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>The Vertex Form of a Parabola</title>
        
        <p>We have learned the standard form of quadratic functions, which is <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>. In this subsection, we will learn another form called the <term>vertex form</term>.</p>

        <p>Using graphing technology, we will graph <m>f(x)=x^2-6x+7</m> and <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m> on the same axes.</p>

            <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=x^2-6x+7</m> and <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[]
                                \addplot+[domain=0:6] {(x-3)^2-2};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(3,-2)} node[below, red] {$(3,-2)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

        <p>We see only one parabola because these are two different forms of the same function. We can see this if we put <m>g(x)</m> in standard form.<md>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=(x-3)^2-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=(x-3)(x-3)-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=x^2-6x+9-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=x^2-6x+7</mrow></md>
        Now it is clear that <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are the same function.</p>

        <p>The function <m>g(x)</m> is written in vertex form, which is very useful because it allows us to read the vertex without doing any calculations. The vertex of the parabola is <m>(3,-2)</m>. We can see those numbers in <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m>. The <m>x</m>-value is the solution to <m>(x-3)=0</m>, and the y-value is the constant at the end.</p>

        <p>Here are the graphs of three more functions in vertex form. Compare each function with the vertex of its graph.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%" margins="0%">
                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-first-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)=(x-2)^2+1</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-0.449:4.449] {(x-2)^2+1};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(2,1)} node[right, red] {$(2,1)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-second-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>s(x)=-\frac{1}{4}(x+1)^2+3</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-7:5.325] {-1/4*(x+1)^2+3};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-1,3)} node[above left, red] {$(-1,3)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-third-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>t(x)=4(x+3)^2-3.5</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.62:-1.38] {4*(x+3)^2-3.5};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-3,-3.5)} node[below, red] {$(-3,-3.5)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

        <p>Notice that the <m>x</m>-coordinate has the opposite sign as the value in the function but the <m>y</m>-coordinate has the same sign as the value in the function. Let's look at an example to understand why. We will substitute <m>x=2</m> in the function <m>r(x)</m> from <xref ref="figure-vertex-in-first-quadrant">Figure</xref>.<md>
            <mrow>r(x)\amp=(x-2)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(\substitute{2})\amp=(\substitute{2}-2)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(2)\amp=(0)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(2)\amp=1</mrow></md>
        The <m>x</m>-value is the solution to <m>(x-2)=0</m>, so it is a positive <m>2</m>. When we plug in <m>x=2</m> we get the value <m>y=1</m>, which is the vertex at <m>(2,1)</m>. Now we can define the vertex form of a quadratic function.</p>

        <fact xml:id="fact-vertex-form">
            <title>Vertex Form of a Quadratic Function</title>
            <idx><h>Vertex Form of a Quadratic Function</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>A quadratic function with the vertex at the point <m>(h,k)</m> is given by <m>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <p>Now you can try reading the vertex of each function.</p>

<!-- TODO: This one could be interactive. -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the vertex of each quadratic function.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p><m>r(x)=-2(x+4)^2+10</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>s(t)=5(t-1)^2+10</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>t(x)=(x-10)^2-5</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>u(v)=3(v+7)^2-13</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>r(x)=-2(x+4)^2+10</m> is <m>(-4,10)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>s(t)=5(t-1)^2+2</m> is <m>(1,2)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>t(x)=(x-10)^2-5</m> is <m>(10,-5)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>u(v)=3(v+7)^2-13</m> is <m>(-7,-13)</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Now let's do the reverse. When given the vertex and the value of <m>a</m>, we can write the function in vertex form.</p>

<!-- TODO: This one could be interactive. -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Write a function, <m>f(x)</m>, with the given vertex and vaue of <m>a</m>.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>Vertex <m>(-2,8)</m>, <m>a=1</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>Vertex <m>(4,-9)</m>, <m>a=-4</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>Vertex <m>(-3,-1)</m>, <m>a=2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>Vertex <m>(5,12)</m>, <m>a=-3</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>The vertex form is <m>f(x)=(x+2)^2+8</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>f(x)=-4(x-4)^2-9</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>f(x)=2(x+3)^2-1</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>f(x)=-3(x-5)^2+12</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Once we read the vertex we can also state the domain and range. All parabolas have a domain of <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m> because we can put in any value to a quadratic function. The range, however, depends on the <m>y</m>-value of the vertex and whether the parabola opens upward or downward. When we have a parabola in vertex form we can read the range from the function. Let's look at the graph of <m>f(x)=2(x-3)^2-5</m> as an example.</p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-domain-and-range-from-vertex-form">
                <caption>The graph of <m>f(x)=2(x-3)^2-5</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
