    <subsection>
        <title>Horizontal and Vertical Shifts</title>

        <p>The graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> has its vertex at the point <m>(0,0)</m>. Now we will compare this with the graph of <m>g(x)=(x-4)^2+1</m> on the same axes.</p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-parabola-shifted-right-and-up">
                <caption>The graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> and <m>g(x)=(x-4)^2+1</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[clip=false]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-2.646:2.646] {x^2};
                                    \addplot+[domain=1.551:6.449] {(x-4)^2+1};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[right] {$(0,0)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(4,1)} node[right] {$(4,1)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}

                            ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Both graphs open upward and have the same shape. Notice that the graph of <m>g(x)</m> is shifted to the right by <m>4</m> units and up by <m>1</m> units because its vertex is <m>(4,1)</m>. Let's look at another one:</p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-parabola-shifted-left-and-up">
                <caption>The graph of <m>f(x)=-x^2</m> and <m>j(x)=-(x+3)^2+4</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[clip=false]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-2.646:2.646] {-x^2};
                                    \addplot+[domain=-6.317:0.317] {-(x+3)^2+4};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[above right] {$(0,0)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-3,4)} node[above right] {$(-3,4)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Both parabolas open downward and have the same shape. The graph of <m>j(x)</m> is shifted to the left by <m>3</m> units and up by <m>4</m> units because its vertex is <m>(-3,4)</m>.</p>

        <p>To summarize this, when a quadratic function is written in vertex form, the <m>h</m>-value is the horizontal shift and the <m>k</m>-value is the vertical shift.</p>

        <p>Now you can try identifying the horizontal and vertical shifts in each function.</p>

