    <subsection>
        <title>The Factored Form of a Parabola</title>

        <p>There is another form of a parabola, called <term>factored form</term>, which we will explore next. Using graphing technology, we will graph <m>f(x)=-x^2+3x+4</m> and <m>g(x)=-(x-4)(x+1)</m> on the same axes.</p>

            <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=-x^2+3x+4</m> and <m>g(x)=-(x-4)(x+1)</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[]
                                \addplot+[domain=-2.14:5.14] {-1*(x-4)*(x+1)};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(4,0)} node[above right, red] {$(4,0)$};
                                 \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-1,0)} node[above left, red] {$(-1,0)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

        <p>These graphs coincide because the functions are equivalent. We can tell by factoring <m>f(x)</m> that it is equivalent to <m>g(x)</m>, or we could multiply <m>g(x)</m> to get back to standard form.<md>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=-(x-4)(x+1)</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=-(x^2-3x-4)</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=-x^2+3x+4</mrow></md>
        Now we can see that <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are the same function.</p>

        <p>Factored form is very useful because we can read the <m>x</m>-intercepts from the function, which in this case are <m>(4,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m>. The <m>x</m>-intercepts are the values that make the factors equal to <m>0</m>, so the <m>x</m>-values have the opposite signs. To demonstrate this, we will find the <m>x</m>-intercepts by solving <m>g(x)=0</m>.<md>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=-(x-4)(x+1)</mrow>
            <mrow>0\amp=-(x-4)(x+1)</mrow></md><md>
            <mrow>x-4\amp=0\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x+1\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=4\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x\amp=-1</mrow></md>
            This shows us that the <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(4,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m>.
        </p>

        <fact xml:id="fact-factored-form">
            <title>Factored Form of a Quadratic Function</title>
            <idx><h>Factored Form of a Quadratic Function</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>A quadratic function with horizontal intercepts at <m>(m,0)</m> and <m>(n,0)</m> is given by <m>f(x)=a(x-m)(x-n)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <p>Now you can try identifying the horizontal intercepts from each factored form.</p>

<!-- TODO: This one could be interactive. -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Write the horizontal intercepts of each function.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p><m>f(x)=-(x+2)(x-4)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(x)=6(x-7)(x-5)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(x)=-2(x+1)(x+4)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(x)=10(x-8)(x+3)</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>The horizontal intercepts are <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(4,0)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The horizontal intercepts are <m>(7,0)</m> and <m>(5,0)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The horizontal intercepts are <m>(-1,0)</m> and <m>(-4,0)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The horizontal intercepts are <m>(8,0)</m> and <m>(-3,0)</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Let's summarize the three forms of a quadratic function:<ul>
            <li><p>Standard Form: <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Vertex Form: <m>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</m>, with vertex <m>(h,k)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Factored Form: <m>f(x)=a(x-m)(x-n)</m>, with <m>x</m>-intercepts at <m>(m,0)</m> and <m>(n,0)</m>.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
    </subsection>
        

